# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: resource-timing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] There are many different ways to measure the performance of a network, as each network is different in nature and design.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] Performance can also be modeled and simulated instead of measured; one example of this is using state transition diagrams to model queuing performance or to use a Network Simulator.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] The available channel bandwidth and achievable signal-to-noise ratio determine the maximum possible throughput.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] It is not generally possible to send more data than dictated by the Shannon-Hartley Theorem.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] The *Time Window* is the period over which the throughput is measured.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] The choice of an appropriate time window will often dominate calculations of throughput, and whether latency is taken into account or not will determine whether the latency affects the throughput or not.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] The speed of light imposes a minimum propagation time on all electromagnetic signals.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] where s is the distance and cm is the speed of light in the medium (roughly 200,000 km/s for most fiber or electrical media, depending on their velocity factor).
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] This approximately means an additional millisecond round-trip delay (RTT) per 100 km (or 62 miles) of distance between hosts.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] Other delays also occur in intermediate nodes.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] In packet switched networks delays can occur due to queueing.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] In digital transmission, the number of **bit errors** is the number of received bits of a data stream over a communication channel that have been altered due to noise, interference, distortion or bit synchronization errors.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] The **bit error rate** or **bit error ratio** (**BER**) is the number of bit errors divided by the total number of transferred bits during a studied time interval.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] BER is a unitless performance measure, often expressed as a percentage.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] The **bit error probability** *pe* is the expectation value of the BER.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] The BER can be considered as an approximate estimate of the bit error probability.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] This estimate is accurate for a long time interval and a high number of bit errors.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] All of the factors above, coupled with user requirements and user perceptions, play a role in determining the perceived 'fastness' or utility, of a network connection.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] The relationship between throughput, latency, and user experience is most aptly understood in the context of a shared network medium, and as a scheduling problem.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] For some systems, latency and throughput are coupled entities.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] In TCP/IP, latency can also directly affect throughput.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] In TCP connections, the large bandwidth-delay product of high latency connections, combined with relatively small TCP window sizes on many devices, effectively causes the throughput of a high latency connection to drop sharply with latency.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] This can be remedied with various techniques, such as increasing the TCP congestion window size, or more drastic solutions, such as packet coalescing, TCP acceleration, and forward error correction, all of which are commonly used for high latency satellite links.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] TCP acceleration converts the TCP packets into a stream that is similar to UDP.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] Because of this, the TCP acceleration software must provide its own mechanisms to ensure the reliability of the link, taking the latency and bandwidth of the link into account, and both ends of the high latency link must support the method used.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] In the Media Access Control (MAC) layer, performance issues such as throughput and end-to-end delay are also addressed.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] Many systems can be characterized as dominated either by throughput limitations or by latency limitations in terms of end-user utility or experience.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] In some cases, hard limits such as the speed of light present unique problems to such systems and nothing can be done to correct this.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] Other systems allow for significant balancing and optimization for best user experience.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] A telecom satellite in geosynchronous orbit imposes a path length of at least 71000 km between transmitter and receiver. which means a minimum delay between message request and message receipt, or latency of 473 ms.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] This delay can be very noticeable and affects satellite phone service regardless of available throughput capacity.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] These long path length considerations are exacerbated when communicating with space probes and other long-range targets beyond Earth's atmosphere.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] The Deep Space Network implemented by NASA is one such system that must cope with these problems.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] Largely latency driven, the GAO has criticized the current architecture.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] Several different methods have been proposed to handle the intermittent connectivity and long delays between packets, such as delay-tolerant networking.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] At interstellar distances, the difficulties in designing radio systems that can achieve any throughput at all are massive.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] In these cases, maintaining communication is a bigger issue than how long that communication takes.
[src:resource-timing/network-performance] Transportation is concerned almost entirely with throughput, which is why physical deliveries of backup tape archives are still largely done by vehicle.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] It’s been available across browsers since September 2017.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] The **`PerformanceResourceTiming`** interface enables retrieval and analysis of detailed network timing data regarding the loading of an application's resources.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] An application can use the timing metrics to determine, for example, the length of time it takes to fetch a specific resource, such as an `XMLHttpRequest`, `<SVG>`, image, or script.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] The interface's properties create a resource loading timeline with high-resolution timestamps for network events such as redirect start and end times, fetch start, DNS lookup start and end times, response start and end times, and more.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] Additionally, the interface extends `PerformanceEntry` with other properties which provide data about the size of the fetched resource as well as the type of resource that initiated the fetch.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] The properties of this interface allow you to calculate certain resource timing metrics.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] By default only 250 resource timing entries are buffered.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] For more information see the resource buffer sizes of the Resource Timing guide.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] Many of the resource timing properties are restricted to return `0` or an empty string when the resource is a cross-origin request.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] To expose cross-origin timing information, the `Timing-Allow-Origin` HTTP response header needs to be set.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] The properties which are returned as `0` by default when loading a resource from an origin other than the one of the web page itself: `redirectStart`, `redirectEnd`, `domainLookupStart`, `domainLookupEnd`, `connectStart`, `connectEnd`, `secureConnectionStart`, `requestStart`, and `responseStart`.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] Returns a `timestamp` that is the difference between the `responseEnd` and the `startTime` properties.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] Returns the `timestamp` for the time a resource fetch started.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] This value is equivalent to `PerformanceResourceTiming.fetchStart`.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] The interface supports the following timestamp properties which you can see in the diagram and are listed in the order in which they are recorded for the fetching of a resource.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] An alphabetical listing is shown in the navigation, at left.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` that represents the start time of the fetch which initiates the redirect.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately after receiving the last byte of the response of the last redirect.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] Returns a `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately before dispatching the `FetchEvent` if a Service Worker thread is already running, or immediately before starting the Service Worker thread if it is not already running.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] If the resource is not intercepted by a Service Worker the property will always return 0.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately before the browser starts to fetch the resource.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately before the browser starts the domain name lookup for the resource.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately after the browser finishes the domain name lookup for the resource.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately before the browser starts to establish the connection to the server to retrieve the resource.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately before the browser starts the handshake process to secure the current connection.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately after the browser finishes establishing the connection to the server to retrieve the resource.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately before the browser starts requesting the resource from the server.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` that represents the interim response time (for example, 100 Continue or 103 Early Hints).
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately after the browser receives the first byte of the response from the server (which may be an interim response).
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` that represents the final headers response time (for example, 200 Success), after any interim response time.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately after the browser receives the last byte of the resource or immediately before the transport connection is closed, whichever comes first.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A string representing a minimized and standardized version of the MIME-type of the fetched resource.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A number that is the size (in octets) received from the fetch (HTTP or cache) of the message body, after removing any applied content encoding.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] Indicates how the resource was delivered — for example from the cache or from a navigational prefetch.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A number representing the size (in octets) received from the fetch (HTTP or cache), of the payload body, before removing any applied content encodings.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A string representing the web platform feature that initiated the performance entry.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A string representing the network protocol used to fetch the resource, as identified by the ALPN Protocol ID (RFC7301).
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A string representing the render-blocking status.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] Either `"blocking"` or `"non-blocking"`.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A number representing the HTTP response status code returned when fetching the resource.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] A number representing the size (in octets) of the fetched resource.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] The size includes the response header fields plus the response payload body.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] An array of `PerformanceServerTiming` entries containing server timing metrics.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] Returns a JSON representation of the `PerformanceResourceTiming` object.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] Example using a `PerformanceObserver`, which notifies of new `resource` performance entries as they are recorded in the browser's performance timeline.
[src:resource-timing/performanceresourcetiming] Use the `buffered` option to access entries from before the observer creation.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] Resource Timing is part of the Performance API and enables retrieving and analyzing detailed network timing data for the loading of an application's resources.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] An application can use the timing metrics to determine, for example, the length of time it takes to load a specific resource (such as an image or a script) either implicitly as part of page load or explicitly from JavaScript, for example using the `fetch()` API.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] Every resource on a document will be represented by a `PerformanceResourceTiming` entry (extending the `PerformanceEntry` interface) with the `entryType` of `"resource"`.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] For each `PerformanceResourceTiming` entry, a *resource loading timeline* will be recorded, with high-resolution timestamps for network events such as redirect start and end times, DNS lookup start and end times, request start, response start and end times, and so on.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] Besides the timestamps, other properties that provide information about the resource are included as well, such the size of the fetched resource, or the type of resource that initiated the fetch.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] See Typical resource timing metrics in the reference page for the `PerformanceResourceTiming` interface.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] (Timestamp diagram listing timestamps in the order in which they are recorded for the fetching of a resource) Figure 1.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] An application can get timestamps for the various stages used to load a resource.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] For example the `startTime`, DNS timestamps, connection set up times and then various resource download times.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] See timestamps in the reference page for the `PerformanceResourceTiming` interface.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] The `PerformanceResourceTiming` interface has three properties that can be used to obtain size data about a resource.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] The `transferSize` property returns the size (in bytes) of the fetched resource including the response header fields plus the response payload body.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] The `encodedBodySize` property returns the size (in octets) received from the fetch (HTTP or cache), of the *payload body*, **before** removing any applied content-codings.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] `decodedBodySize` returns the size (in octets) received from the fetch (HTTP or cache) of the *message body*, **after** removing any applied content-codings.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] The `PerformanceResourceTiming` interface provides additional resources information.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] Consult the reference docs for the full list of properties.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] If your website or application fetches more than 250 resources and you want to record more than 250 `PerformanceResourceTiming` entries, you need to increase the size of the resource timing buffer.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] To set the size of the browser's performance resource data buffer, use the `Performance.setResourceTimingBufferSize()` method, and to clear the browser's performance resource data buffer, use the `Performance.clearResourceTimings()` method.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] To get notified when the browser's resource timing buffer is full, listen for the `resourcetimingbufferfull` event.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] The following call allows 500 `"resource"` performance entries in the browser's performance timeline.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] For more information, see also Managing buffer sizes.
[src:resource-timing/resource-timing-api] For more information on the fields affected, see Cross-origin timing information in the reference page for the `PerformanceResourceTiming` interface.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] TTFB measures the duration from the user or client making an HTTP request to the first byte of the page being received by the client's browser.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] This time is made up of the socket connection time, the time taken to send and the time taken to get the first byte of the page.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] Although sometimes misunderstood as a post-DNS calculation, the original calculation of TTFB in networking always includes network latency in measuring the time it takes for a resource to begin loading.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] Often, a smaller (faster) TTFB size is seen as a benchmark of a well-configured server application.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] For example, a lower time to first byte could point to fewer dynamic calculations being performed by the webserver, although this is often due to caching at either the DNS, server, or application level.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] More commonly, a very low TTFB is observed with statically served web pages, while larger TTFB is often seen with larger, dynamic data requests being pulled from a database.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] Time to first byte is important to a webpage since it indicates pages that load slowly due to server-side calculations that might be better served as client-side scripting.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] Often this includes simple scripts and calculations like transitioning images that are not gifs and are transitioned using JavaScript to modify their transparency levels.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] This can often speed up a website by downloading multiple smaller images through sockets instead of one large image.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] However this technique is more intensive on the client's computer and on older PCs can slow the webpage down when actually rendering.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] TTFB is often used by web search engines like Google and Yahoo to improve search rankings since a website will respond to the request faster and be usable before other websites would be able to.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] There are downsides to this metric since a web-server can send only the first part of the header before the content is even ready to send to reduce their TTFB.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] While this may seem deceptive it can be used to inform the user that the webserver is in fact active and will respond with content shortly.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] There are several reasons why this deception is useful, including that it causes a persistent connection to be created, which results in fewer retry attempts from a browser or user since it has already received a connection and is now preparing for the content download.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] Load time is how long it takes for a webpage to be loaded and usable by a browser.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] Often in web page delivery a page is compressed in the Gzip format to make the size of the download smaller.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] This practice prevents the first byte from being sent until the compression is complete and increases the TTFB significantly.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] TTFB can go from 100–200 ms to 1000–20000 ms, but the page will load much faster and be ready for the user in a much smaller amount of time.
[src:resource-timing/time-to-first-byte] Many websites see a common 5–10× increase in TTFB but a much faster browser response time garnering 20% load-time decrease.
[src:resource-timing/transfersize] It’s been available across browsers since March 2023.
[src:resource-timing/transfersize] The **`transferSize`** read-only property represents the size (in octets) of the fetched resource.
[src:resource-timing/transfersize] The size includes the response header fields plus the response payload body (as defined by RFC7230).
[src:resource-timing/transfersize] If the resource is fetched from a local cache, or if it is a cross-origin resource, this property returns zero.
[src:resource-timing/transfersize] For environments not supporting the `responseStatus` property, the `transferSize` property can be used to determine cache hits.
[src:resource-timing/transfersize] If `transferSize` is zero and the resource has a non-zero decoded body size (meaning the resource is same-origin or has `Timing-Allow-Origin`), the resource was fetched from a local cache.
[src:resource-timing/transfersize] If the value of the `transferSize` property is `0` and wasn't loaded from a local cache, the resource might be a cross-origin request.
[src:resource-timing/transfersize] To expose cross-origin content size information, the `Timing-Allow-Origin` HTTP response header needs to be set.
